<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-04-27T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-04-27T12:00:00-05:00" n="625" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d625">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/3354: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Moore</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-27T12:00:00-05:00">April 27,
                                1929—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 1:50 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>84. My telegram number 83.<note n="25" xml:id="d625fn25"><hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi></note> Saw President Leguia at 11:30
                            this morning. He said: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Under no circumstances or conditions would I do anything in the
                                    slightest way to embarrass President Hoover for whom I have the
                                    greatest admiration. I shall ask to have the clause withdrawn
                                    immediately.”</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <p>He thoroughly agrees with your viewpoint, which he says is most logical.
                            He will see the Chilean Ambassador at 12:30 today. Have you any further
                            instructions or suggestions?</p>
                        <p>More to follow.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>